Q9. Purpose of a Confusion Matrix
A Confusion Matrix evaluates classification model performance by comparing actual and predicted classes.
It contains:
True Positive (TP)
True Negative (TN)
False Positive (FP)
False Negative (FN)
Difference from Correlation Matrix
Confusion Matrix	                           \                            Correlation Matrix
Evaluates classification performance	        \                Measures relationships between variables
Uses actual vs predicted values                \                       	Uses feature values
Contains TP, TN, FP, FN	                        \             Contains correlation coefficients (-1 to +1)

Q10. Comparison of Algorithms
Algorithm	Main Idea
Decision Tree	Makes decisions using a series of if-else rules arranged like a tree.
KNN (K-Nearest Neighbors)	Classifies a data point based on the majority class of its nearest neighbors.
SVM (Support Vector Machine)	Finds the best boundary (hyperplane) that separates different classes.
Linear Regression	Predicts continuous values by fitting a straight line to the data.
Neural Network	Learns complex patterns through interconnected layers of artificial neurons.
